          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">30 years since Srebrenica</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>Summary: The Srebrenica massacre, the worst mass killing in Europe since WWII, helped shape the system of international justice.</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           <strong>The what:</strong> In July 1995, during the Bosnian War, Bosnian Serb forces killed more than 8,000 Bosniak men and boys (mostly Muslims) in a UN-declared ‚Äúsafe area‚Äù of <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-14-jul-25-analysis-h1-7-srebrenica?source=website" target="_blank">Srebrenica</a>. The massacre pushed NATO to intervene militarily, which led to the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-14-jul-25-analysis-h1-8-dayton-accords?source=website" target="_blank">Dayton Accords</a> (a peace agreement that ended the Bosnian War).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The why:</strong> The war in Bosnia began after Yugoslavia fell apart. Bosnian Serb leaders wanted to take control of parts of eastern Bosnia near the Serbian border and drive out the mostly Muslim population. Srebrenica was one of those towns. In 1995, they launched a military operation to take control of it and, once the town fell, they separated the men and boys from the rest and carried out mass executions.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           <strong>The impact:</strong> This massacre led to global efforts to hold war criminals accountable. It promoted the creation of special UN Tribunals and, eventually, the permanent International Criminal Court. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          But the Dayton Peace Agreement that ended the war also locked Bosnia into an ethnic power-sharing system (where political power is divided among Bosniaks, Serbs, and Croats) that still makes Bosnia‚Äôs politics unstable and difficult to manage (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-14-jul-25-analysis-h1-9-more-about-bosnia?source=website" target="_blank">more about Bosnia</a>).
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
